result.execSummary:
The defendant Kelly J. Kotora was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Bail Jumping-Felony, a class H felony, Wisconsin Statutes 946.49(1)(b).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

supervisions.notes: Concurrent to 15CF831.  Probation Review Hearing scheduled in Br 6 on 7-27-2016 at 3:30 pm.

miscConds.notes:
The Defendant is to undergo any counseling the agent finds appropriate and must comply with any recommended treatment/assessment/counseling.  Defendant may not withdraw from any ordered program without permission of the agent and/or provider.  The Defendant is to complete AODA assessment and comply with any treatment recommended.  The Defendant is to maintain absolute sobriety - no alcohol or drugs unless prescribed by a physician.  The Defendant's employment is per the Agent.  The Defendant is to provide a biological specimen for DNA analysis.  The Defendant is not to go into any bars, taverns or businesses where the primary purpose is to sell alcohol (can be in a restaurant, but not the bar area).  The Defendant is to apply to be in Drug Treatment Court Program within 30 days.  The Defendant is to live at W2522 Skyview Court, Appleton, WI.  The Defendant is not to have any alcohol or drugs in the home.  The Defendant is to work with the Agent on an after care program.  The Agent should try to get her in an inpatient program.  The Defendant is to pick a book on recovery within 30 days.  She is to send a letter to the Court about what book is picked.  She has 90 days to read the book and send a copy of a book report to the Court and the Agent.  If probation is revoked or discharged with outstanding financial obligations, a civil judgment shall be entered for the balance due, and/or other collection means, such as income assignment will be issued.

**07-27-2016 - Court allows defendant to change her residence but it must be approved by her Agent.
